04550nam a22006135i 9780822387497DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223874977 a10.1515/97808223874972doi  a(DE-B1597)554564  a(OCoLC)1055304238  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF869.L89bA27 2005 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.8/009794/941 aSong, Min Hyoung, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStrange Future :bPessimism and the 1992 Los Angeles Riots /cMin Hyoung Song. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (300 p.) :b17 b&w photos, 2 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: When the Strange Erupts in Culture -- t1. Racial Geography of Southern California -- t2. The Black Body in Pain: Rodney King and Strange Days -- t3. Culture of Wounding: The Riots and Twilight -- t4. Mourning Los Angeles -- t5. A Diasporic Future? Historical Trauma and Native Speaker -- tEpilogue: Bearers of Bad News -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSometime near the start of the 1990s, the future became a place of national decline. The United States had entered a period of great anxiety fueled by the shrinking of the white middle class, the increasingly visible misery of poor urban blacks, and the mass immigration of nonwhites. Perhaps more than any other event marking the passage through these dark years, the 1992 Los Angeles riots have sparked imaginative and critical works reacting to this profound pessimism. Focusing on a wide range of these creative works, Min Hyoung Song shows how the L.A. riots have become a cultural-literary event-an important reference and resource for imagining the social problems plaguing the United States and its possible futures.Song considers works that address the riots and often the traumatic place of the Korean American community within them: the independent documentary Sa-I-Gu (Korean for April 29, the date the riots began), Chang-rae Lee's novel Native Speaker, the commercial film Strange Days, and the experimental drama of Anna Deavere Smith, among many others. He describes how cultural producers have used the riots to examine the narrative of national decline, manipulating language and visual elements, borrowing and refashioning familiar tropes, and, perhaps most significantly, repeatedly turning to metaphors of bodily suffering to convey a sense of an unraveling social fabric. Song argues that these aesthetic experiments offer ways of revisiting the traumas of the past in order to imagine more survivable futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAfrican AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aAmerican literaturexKorean American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEthnicity in literature. 0aKorean AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aPessimismxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aRace relations in literature. 0aRace riotszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrban poorzCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387497zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387497423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822387497.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles